</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="327" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="48.[1399,2608,735,1674]" pageId="48" pageNumber="327">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1401,2096,1369,1398]" pageId="48" pageNumber="327">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
Smoky Mountain Voleslive in large, dense colonies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="327" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="48.[1399,2608,735,1674]" pageId="48" pageNumber="327">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1401,1749,1444,1477]" pageId="48" pageNumber="327">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List (as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Buchner" baseAuthorityYear="1889" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Lasiopodomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="48" pageNumber="327" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fuscus">Lasiopodomys fuscus</taxonomicName>
). Threats to the Smoky Mountain Vole are unknown. Poisoning of small mammals on the Tibetan Plateau might have reduced density, but new studies are needed to confirm this.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
